1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:03,181
Hey Michelle, how are you today?

2
00:00:03,181 --> 00:00:06,202
I'm good, Lindsay. How are you?

3
00:00:06,202 --> 00:00:07,209
Fantastic, fantastic.

4
00:00:07,209 --> 00:00:10,742
What are we getting into in All Ears English today, Michelle?

5
00:00:10,742 --> 00:00:13,053
Well Lindsay, I have a question.

6
00:00:13,053 --> 00:00:18,600
What would you say is one of the top experiences you've had in the past year?

7
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:22,584
Oh my gosh, it's hard to say.

8
00:00:22,584 --> 00:00:25,560
But probably hiking in Slovenia was amazing.

9
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:30,061
That altitude and just being in a new place was awesome.

10
00:00:30,061 --> 00:00:32,795
It's usually a travel experience for me.

11
00:00:32,795 --> 00:00:34,358
What about you, Michelle?

12
00:00:34,358 --> 00:00:41,680
Oh yeah, for me, I guess it was a whirlwind of a year.

13
00:00:41,680 --> 00:00:44,200
So I would just say moving in general.

14
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:49,500
Okay, I don't know if it was like the top experience, as if you would be traveling.

15
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:55,478
But it was pretty awesome to move into a house and just kind of start building a new life.

16
00:00:55,478 --> 00:00:57,520
So I would say that.

17
00:00:57,520 --> 00:01:00,040
Yes, I love that, I love that.

18
00:01:00,040 --> 00:01:04,114
So, experience — you asked me about my top experience of the year.

19
00:01:04,114 --> 00:01:06,893
Is that what we're talking about today on the show?

20
00:01:06,893 --> 00:01:07,726
We are, we are.

21
00:01:07,726 --> 00:01:10,992
We're actually doing a miniseries — this is the first part.

22
00:01:10,992 --> 00:01:16,952
And guys, stay tuned, because the second part is going to be about a different way to use the word experience.

23
00:01:16,952 --> 00:01:20,286
And we're going to do this over on the Business English podcast.

24
00:01:20,286 --> 00:01:29,781
So don't think, if you're not looking to excel at work — if you're just listening for fun — that it won't help. It still will.

25
00:01:29,781 --> 00:01:35,015
This is not just for business, but it's going to be really good for the Business English podcast.

26
00:01:35,015 --> 00:01:43,760
So go ahead on over to that one and hit follow, because that one is coming out very soon.

27
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:45,200
I love it, I love it.

28
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:49,802
Yeah, go ahead and hit follow, hit the follow button, guys, so you don't miss a single episode.

29
00:01:49,802 --> 00:01:52,767
Either here on All Ears English or over on Business English.

30
00:01:52,767 --> 00:01:56,852
But Michelle, we do have some poll results to share today.

31
00:01:56,852 --> 00:01:58,404
We do, we do.

32
00:01:58,404 --> 00:02:03,661
All right, so this is from episode 2371, 'Is This Seat Taken?'

33
00:02:03,661 --> 00:02:06,626
And Lindsay, what was the poll question?

34
00:02:06,626 --> 00:02:13,213
Okay, the poll question was: is it acceptable to save seats in crowded places in your culture?

35
00:02:13,213 --> 00:02:16,460
We had a whole interesting conversation around saving seats.

36
00:02:16,460 --> 00:02:21,284
And we thought maybe it's kind of cultural, this idea of saving seats.

37
00:02:21,284 --> 00:02:24,848
And especially saving more than one seat next to you, right?

38
00:02:24,848 --> 00:02:27,116
Yes, that was fun.

39
00:02:27,116 --> 00:02:31,227
So, is it acceptable to save seats in crowded places in your culture?

40
00:02:31,227 --> 00:02:33,120
So Lindsay, what were the results?

41
00:02:33,120 --> 00:02:38,560
All right, so our listeners — the verdict is: yes, it is acceptable, for 68% of our listeners.

42
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:42,920
And no for 31% of people that are listening to the show.

43
00:02:42,920 --> 00:02:44,809
Very interesting breakdown here, Michelle.

44
00:02:44,809 --> 00:02:48,240
Yeah, I would definitely be curious to learn more about it.

45
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:51,373
It's always those things that you don't think too much about, right?

46
00:02:51,373 --> 00:02:54,618
We don't think about, oh, saving seats around the world.

47
00:02:54,618 --> 00:03:00,939
But it's always when you travel — those are the things that you kind of pick up on, how things are different.

48
00:03:00,939 --> 00:03:03,760
But you don't think about it ahead of time, right?

49
00:03:03,760 --> 00:03:04,613
It's true, absolutely.

50
00:03:04,613 --> 00:03:07,027
Wow, there are so many differences around the world.

51
00:03:07,027 --> 00:03:10,328
But I think the thing that brings us together is the desire for connection.

52
00:03:10,328 --> 00:03:13,765
I mean, that's what we're coming together around here in the show.

53
00:03:13,765 --> 00:03:17,981
So using the correct vocabulary words is one way to do that, right Michelle?

54
00:03:17,981 --> 00:03:19,205
Love it. Yeah, exactly.

55
00:03:19,205 --> 00:03:28,368
So, talking about experience — we're going to talk about some really useful ways to refer to an important situation, something you've done, something like that.

56
00:03:28,368 --> 00:03:35,864
So this is, you know, when we talk about work experience, that's kind of a different way to use that word.

57
00:03:35,864 --> 00:03:41,520
So we're going to talk about a slightly special way to use it.

58
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:43,480
So okay Lindsay, what's the first one?

59
00:03:43,480 --> 00:03:47,600
Okay, so the first one we're talking about today is 'a' or 'an experience.'

60
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:54,329
Right, so this could be anything — a way to describe something that you've done, again, like you said.

61
00:03:54,329 --> 00:04:00,208
So throwing out some common ones, here we have: a wonderful experience, a terrible experience, a learning experience.

62
00:04:00,208 --> 00:04:02,416
What else, Michelle, might we say?

63
00:04:02,416 --> 00:04:07,114
You could say an unforgettable experience, a unique experience, a special experience.

64
00:04:07,114 --> 00:04:11,336
Sometimes somebody might even say a once-in-a-lifetime experience, right?

65
00:04:11,336 --> 00:04:14,631
It's a cliche, but it's a good one, I think.

66
00:04:14,631 --> 00:04:15,585
Right, exactly, exactly.

67
00:04:15,585 --> 00:04:17,149
So let's do some examples here.

68
00:04:17,149 --> 00:04:20,902
So, well, this one is for me.

69
00:04:20,902 --> 00:04:25,120
"I had a wonderful experience living in London. I will never forget it."

70
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:26,104
Oh, for sure.

71
00:04:26,104 --> 00:04:34,000
Any kind of — like we said at the top of the show — any kind of a chance to live abroad or travel is usually a wonderful experience.

72
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:37,221
Sometimes it can be hard, right? But wonderful.

73
00:04:37,221 --> 00:04:39,011
Yeah, or here's another example.

74
00:04:39,011 --> 00:04:43,158
"I just had the best experience I've ever had at a nail salon."

75
00:04:43,158 --> 00:04:47,162
Best experience you've ever had at a nail salon — you have to go there!

76
00:04:47,162 --> 00:04:49,701
I actually went to get my nails done recently.

77
00:04:49,701 --> 00:04:55,691
Yeah, I never do, but I had a photo shoot and I was like, 'Oh, I have to do my nails, right?'

78
00:04:55,691 --> 00:04:57,549
It was fun, it was like pampering.

79
00:04:57,549 --> 00:05:00,647
You put your nails in there and, you know, it was great.

80
00:05:00,647 --> 00:05:04,104
Did you get a color, or were you more of a neutral?

81
00:05:04,104 --> 00:05:08,768
I just got the neutral — just the gel and the neutral.

82
00:05:08,768 --> 00:05:12,160
Oh, gel — I know, so fancy. Yes, exactly.

83
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:13,600
All right, here we go.

84
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:16,000
"You have to look at this as a learning experience."

85
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,040
"You may not love every minute of it, but it will get you to the next level."

86
00:05:21,040 --> 00:05:26,829
So yeah, I think we do throw around this idea of experience, and describing the experience, a lot.

87
00:05:26,829 --> 00:05:31,075
And it's part of kind of coming of age too, in American culture.

88
00:05:31,075 --> 00:05:33,560
Going to college is a learning experience.

89
00:05:33,560 --> 00:05:38,295
Separating from your parents when you're 18, 19 years old is an experience, right?

90
00:05:38,295 --> 00:05:39,242
Yep, yep, exactly.

91
00:05:39,242 --> 00:05:45,735
I mean, Lindsay — you were talking about Slovenia, but any other experiences you want to share?

92
00:05:45,735 --> 00:05:50,537
What would you say has been your most unforgettable experience while traveling?

93
00:05:50,537 --> 00:05:54,537
I know that's probably a tough question.

94
00:05:54,537 --> 00:05:56,739
Yeah, they're all pretty unforgettable.

95
00:05:56,739 --> 00:06:00,621
I mean, living in Japan dramatically altered my life.

96
00:06:00,621 --> 00:06:05,566
I just had dinner with — did I mention this on the show? — someone I hadn't seen in 20 years.

97
00:06:05,566 --> 00:06:12,536
Someone I had lived — not lived with — in Japan, but we were very close, and we were trained together as a group.

98
00:06:12,536 --> 00:06:14,144
And it changed me, you know?

99
00:06:14,144 --> 00:06:19,570
When you go do something like that when you're 24 years old, it changes how you envision the rest of your life.

100
00:06:19,570 --> 00:06:23,800
What kind of work you're going to do, and how your life is going to look.

101
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:26,680
Right, so that would be it for me.

102
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:29,200
Yeah, absolutely. All right, love it. Okay.

103
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:37,680
So another thing you can just say is — and this is, I love this — do you ever say 'it was an experience'?

104
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:43,543
Yeah, and I love this because we could say an awful lot without saying very much, right?

105
00:06:43,543 --> 00:06:44,160
It's emphatic.

106
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:48,391
It's generally used to say something was a little crazy, maybe a little chaotic.

107
00:06:48,391 --> 00:06:52,030
Maybe there's a — yeah, we're hinting at something maybe not that great, right?

108
00:06:52,030 --> 00:06:53,380
Let's give an example, Michelle.

109
00:06:53,380 --> 00:06:54,895
All right, little role play here.

110
00:06:54,895 --> 00:06:59,484
"Hey, I heard you took your kids on the plane — how was your flight with your kids?"

111
00:06:59,484 --> 00:07:01,702
"Woo, it was an experience."

112
00:07:01,702 --> 00:07:09,091
So when you hear me say that, what do I possibly mean?

113
00:07:09,091 --> 00:07:14,909
I gather that you survived it, right? You came out of it, but it was not easy, right?

114
00:07:14,909 --> 00:07:17,019
That's the key, right? Right, exactly, exactly.

115
00:07:17,019 --> 00:07:21,268
And maybe you don't want to go into all the details for me today.

116
00:07:21,268 --> 00:07:26,504
But you're just — I get it, okay? All right, it was a little challenging, what she did.

117
00:07:26,504 --> 00:07:27,712
Yeah, right, right, right.

118
00:07:27,712 --> 00:07:29,192
Something was a little wild.

119
00:07:29,192 --> 00:07:35,187
It could — I mean, it could be positive, but it's mostly to say it was wild or chaotic.

120
00:07:35,187 --> 00:07:39,840
I mean, have you had any experiences like that recently?

121
00:07:39,840 --> 00:07:43,160
Oh, wild and chaotic experiences like that, Michelle?

122
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:47,402
No, not recently — things have been relatively smooth, I would say.

123
00:07:47,402 --> 00:07:54,240
But, although, when I came back from California a few weeks ago, I was carrying back some heavy items.

124
00:07:54,240 --> 00:08:02,472
And I had to load up the suitcase and lift it from the ground to pull it up into the overhead bin.

125
00:08:02,472 --> 00:08:07,326
That was kind of unwieldy and crazy, so I had to use the leg muscles.

126
00:08:07,326 --> 00:08:11,760
Yeah, so you could say, 'Oh my gosh, that was an experience.'

127
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:15,064
Yeah, for me it was going on the plane with both of my kids.

128
00:08:15,064 --> 00:08:16,480
That's a true, a true thing.

129
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:22,984
I can't imagine. I've seen it on TV, but I just don't know how people do it.

130
00:08:22,984 --> 00:08:25,391
All right Michelle, we are back.

131
00:08:25,391 --> 00:08:30,036
So is there another way that we use this term experience?

132
00:08:30,036 --> 00:08:34,742
Yeah, so this is one that comes about quite frequently, I think.

133
00:08:34,742 --> 00:08:39,275
Have you ever heard somebody say 'you're paying for the experience'?

134
00:08:39,275 --> 00:08:43,425
Yes, you hear that. Yeah, yeah, totally.

135
00:08:43,425 --> 00:08:46,776
Especially when we're paying too much for something, right?

136
00:08:46,776 --> 00:08:50,358
Exactly, yep.

137
00:08:50,358 --> 00:08:53,139
So yeah, this is an interesting one.

138
00:08:53,139 --> 00:08:59,869
I'm pretty sure this episode was probably inspired by this expression, because I feel like it comes up a lot.

139
00:08:59,869 --> 00:09:05,991
So this is used when you want to say something is maybe overpriced for the service provided.

140
00:09:05,991 --> 00:09:12,876
Or simply that the quality isn't wonderful, but there's something special or unique about it that makes it worth it.

141
00:09:12,876 --> 00:09:20,282
So to me, I think of like a theme restaurant — do you remember, did you have something called the Rainforest Cafe?

142
00:09:20,282 --> 00:09:22,364
Yeah, it sounds familiar, sounds familiar.

143
00:09:22,364 --> 00:09:26,578
Yeah, growing up, you know, we loved to go to the Rainforest Cafe.

144
00:09:26,578 --> 00:09:31,600
And I actually don't know how much it was, because I was a kid, but I'm assuming it was expensive.

145
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:36,667
And it's a really cool atmosphere.

146
00:09:36,667 --> 00:09:41,566
It's not that there's anything special about the food, but you would say, 'Oh, you're paying for the experience.'

147
00:09:41,566 --> 00:09:46,720
Another one I can think of is — do you ever go to the Stardust Diner in New York?

148
00:09:46,720 --> 00:09:48,091
It sounds very familiar.

149
00:09:48,091 --> 00:09:52,468
I mean, that one — or what comes to mind for me is Benihana.

150
00:09:52,468 --> 00:09:57,752
Ah, that's the ultimate, right? Because you're paying to watch people flip things in the air.

151
00:09:57,752 --> 00:10:04,613
And you bring kids and they love it — there's onions flying and there's fire going, and a hibachi.

152
00:10:04,613 --> 00:10:07,787
Yep, and the food's maybe not outstanding.

153
00:10:07,787 --> 00:10:14,466
You could get better Japanese food somewhere else, but you're paying for the experience, right?

154
00:10:14,466 --> 00:10:15,793
Yes, exactly.

155
00:10:15,793 --> 00:10:21,131
Or let me think — there was one I wanted to share.

156
00:10:21,131 --> 00:10:25,180
Wait, what's another — wait, wait, wait, oh my gosh, I'll come back to it.

157
00:10:25,180 --> 00:10:28,340
But so let's do a little role play, okay? Here we go.

158
00:10:28,340 --> 00:10:29,657
"So how was the food?"

159
00:10:29,657 --> 00:10:34,664
"Uh, the food was okay, but really that's not what it's about — you're paying for the experience."

160
00:10:34,664 --> 00:10:38,665
Of course, of course — acrobats at your seat, that's so much fun.

161
00:10:38,665 --> 00:10:44,396
And sometimes it's okay — yeah, we have to decide when we want to pay for the experience.

162
00:10:44,396 --> 00:10:48,013
Maybe that's the event of the weekend, right? And that's what we're paying for.

163
00:10:48,013 --> 00:10:50,507
But sometimes you're thinking, okay, I just want good food.

164
00:10:50,507 --> 00:10:52,864
So I'm going to go more low-key and unknown, right?

165
00:10:52,864 --> 00:10:56,400
Right, so — actually, now I know what I was going to say.

166
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:59,029
I was going to go back to the Stardust Diner.

167
00:10:59,029 --> 00:11:03,621
So the Stardust Diner is a restaurant in New York, and it's very popular.

168
00:11:03,621 --> 00:11:08,724
And it's kind of aspiring actors and actresses who sing at your seat.

169
00:11:08,724 --> 00:11:13,600
Well, not at your seat, but they kind of go all around the restaurant — they take turns singing.

170
00:11:13,600 --> 00:11:20,425
And they are incredible — I mean, they are just incredible, incredible singers.

171
00:11:20,425 --> 00:11:27,364
But I wouldn't, like — and the food is diner food, and it's expensive diner food.

172
00:11:27,364 --> 00:11:30,306
It's expensive food, I mean.

173
00:11:30,306 --> 00:11:34,268
Like, I took my son there and we got like a bagel and a tuna melt.

174
00:11:34,268 --> 00:11:41,415
I mean, this was probably a year ago, and it's just overpriced — the food is overpriced.

175
00:11:41,415 --> 00:11:45,995
But what you would say in that case is, 'It's okay, you're paying for the experience.'

176
00:11:45,995 --> 00:11:51,026
It's that there's something special that kind of warrants the extra money that you spend.

177
00:11:51,026 --> 00:11:55,975
Yes. Or we also say 'paying for the convenience,' but that's another episode for another day, right?

178
00:11:55,975 --> 00:11:59,609
Another episode for another day. Oh, that's a good one. Yes, yes.

179
00:11:59,609 --> 00:12:02,418
A bodega or something — totally different thing.

180
00:12:02,418 --> 00:12:04,555
Yeah, for sure, totally different thing.

181
00:12:04,555 --> 00:12:10,144
But have you had any experiences recently where you felt you were paying for the experience?

182
00:12:10,144 --> 00:12:12,556
Well, like I said, Benihana — we went there.

183
00:12:12,556 --> 00:12:16,349
I went with my extended family on Christmas Eve, or around the holidays.

184
00:12:16,349 --> 00:12:20,396
And I was like, 'Are we really going here?'

185
00:12:20,396 --> 00:12:25,821
I didn't pay, though, so you know — my family treats, so I'm cool with it. That's fine.

186
00:12:25,821 --> 00:12:30,920
So all right, that is a really fun one — I like that expression.

187
00:12:30,920 --> 00:12:33,622
So Lindsay, let's do a role play here.

188
00:12:33,622 --> 00:12:39,210
In this role play, you just went to a new spa, and I am asking you about it.

189
00:12:39,210 --> 00:12:41,816
Oh yes, okay, here we go.

190
00:12:41,816 --> 00:12:44,570
"All right, so how was it?"

191
00:12:44,570 --> 00:12:46,407
"It was an experience."

192
00:12:46,407 --> 00:12:49,621
"Really? Yeah, I mean, it was good."

193
00:12:49,621 --> 00:12:55,444
"There were tons of people there, super crowded. I don't know, maybe I'll go somewhere else next time."

194
00:12:55,444 --> 00:13:00,093
"Oh well, you could try my place — it's pretty expensive, but you're paying for the experience."

195
00:13:00,093 --> 00:13:06,560
"They have the most beautiful rooms and play the best music, and the staff is so nice — I'd say it's worth it."

196
00:13:06,560 --> 00:13:11,515
"Okay, maybe I'll call them. I want to get the best experience possible."

197
00:13:11,515 --> 00:13:13,040
"Definitely, you deserve it."

198
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:18,640
Nice, nice. Yeah, it makes me think of — have you ever heard of a beer spa?

199
00:13:18,640 --> 00:13:20,740
This is so — no? — so bad.

200
00:13:20,740 --> 00:13:25,326
So there is a beer spa in Denver, and I've been to it a couple times.

201
00:13:25,326 --> 00:13:30,268
Where literally they put beer and hops in the water, and it's supposed to have anti-inflammatory properties.

202
00:13:30,268 --> 00:13:32,697
I'm not sure if I believe that.

203
00:13:32,697 --> 00:13:37,105
And then you can drink beer in the spa — it's a whole thing.

204
00:13:37,105 --> 00:13:39,474
So that is an experience, Michelle, right?

205
00:13:39,474 --> 00:13:41,834
That's definitely probably paying for the experience.

206
00:13:41,834 --> 00:13:51,456
It's like there's something so unique or special about it that you bake that into the price of the actual quality of something.

207
00:13:51,456 --> 00:13:53,088
It's so crazy, it's so crazy.

208
00:13:53,088 --> 00:13:57,164
So that's the kind of thing, you know — a once-in-a-lifetime experience.

209
00:13:57,164 --> 00:14:01,576
I probably wouldn't go back there regularly — I tried it once, it didn't knock my socks off.

210
00:14:01,576 --> 00:14:04,964
You know — bonus phrase for today: 'knock my socks off.'

211
00:14:04,964 --> 00:14:09,552
Knock socks off — yeah, I'm gonna put that one in there. That's a great one.

212
00:14:09,552 --> 00:14:13,200
Well, let's go through the role play, Michelle. So what did I say?

213
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:17,808
Mhm, okay, so I said, 'So how was it?' And you said, 'It was an experience.'

214
00:14:17,808 --> 00:14:21,621
And when somebody says that, you know there's more to the story.

215
00:14:21,621 --> 00:14:27,177
Um, yes — there's a lot packed in there, there's a lot implied by saying that.

216
00:14:27,177 --> 00:14:31,288
And you have to use your intonation there, you know.

217
00:14:31,288 --> 00:14:34,980
